g.text: Coffee Table: A large table with two huge vacuum-insulated thermal coffee dispensers. Someone has forgotten a small plastic card next to the stacks of cups.
You: Look into one of the old coffee cups.
You: Uh-huh, great. I somehow doubt old coffee is how the police solve investigations.
Inland Empire: A clue about the person behind all the murders.
Logic: Yeah. Of course. It's certainly not just an example of *par√©idolie*, noticing patterns in noise. Worth it.
Inland Empire: If you can't trust your own eyes, who can you trust...
Coffee Table: If you squint your eyes enough the coffee grounds almost seem to make up two letters: F... and K.

Coffee Table: You snatch up the red plastic card. It features a black contour of a crane lifting a container. The name 'Etienne Hogarth' is written in the middle, below it in smaller text: 'Member of the board'. It comes with a magnetic strip -- meant to open electronic doors.
Inland Empire: It's meaningful, I *swear*! You just wait... I've got the case nearly busted wide open.
You: It *is* a sign! Just like a remote viewer would operate. Signs hidden inside the mundane...
Coffee Table: You see nothing exceptional. It's a dirty cup, smudged brown, with old ground coffee stuck to the bottom... slowly getting mouldy.
You: Huh, okay. Thanks, this certainly wasn't a waste of time.
You: What am I supposed to see here?
Coffee Table: You throw the cup back into the trash bin.
Inland Empire: If you can't trust your own eyes, who can you trust? Certainly not Kim. He's so... suspicious.
Inland Empire: Peer into a discarded coffee cup!
Inland Empire: You got it, pal. I would *never* make such a thing up.
